[31m-     │    ├── helper.h[m
[31m-     │    ├── ...[m
[31m-   ```[m
[31m-2. Source `helper.h` near the top of your `.keymap` file:[m
[31m-    ```C++[m
[31m-    #include "../zmk-nodefree-config/helper.h"[m
[31m-    ```[m
[31m-3. Customize your keyboard's `.keymap` file. See [example.keymap](example.keymap) or [my[m
[31m-   personal zmk-config](https://github.com/urob/zmk-config/blob/main/config/base.keymap)[m
[31m-   for a complete configuration, and read the documentation below for details.[m
[31m-[m
[31m-## Configuration details[m
[31m-[m
[31m-### ZMK\_BEHAVIOR[m
[31m-[m
[31m-`ZMK_BEHAVIOR` can be used to create any of the following ZMK behaviors: caps-word,[m
[31m-hold-tap, key-repeat, macro, mod-morph, sticky-key, tap-dance or tri-state.[m
[31m-[m
[31m-**Syntax:** `ZMK_BEHAVIOR(name, type, specification)`[m
[31m-* `name`: a unique string chosen by the user (e.g., `my_behavior`). The new behavior can[m
[31m-  be added to the keymap using `&name` (e.g., `&my_behavior`).[m
[31m-* `type`: the behavior to be created. It must be one of the following:[m
[31m-  `caps_word`, `hold_tap`, `key_repeat`, `macro`, `macro_one_param`,[m
[31m-  `macro_two_param`, `mod_morph`, `sticky_key`, `tap_dance` or `tri_state`.[m
[31m-  Note that multiword behaviors are separated by underscores (`_`).[m
[31m-* `specification`: the custom behavior code. It should contain the[m
[31m-  body of the corresponding [ZMK behavior configuration](https://zmk.dev/docs/config/behaviors)[m
[31m-  without the `label`, `#binding-cells` and `compatible` properties and without the[m
[31m-  surrounding node-specification.[m
[31m-[m
[31m-#### Example 1: Creating a custom "homerow mod" tap-hold behavior[m
[31m-[m
[31m-```C++[m
[31m-ZMK_BEHAVIOR(hrm, hold_tap,[m
[31m-    flavor = "balanced";[m
[31m-    tapping-term-ms = <280>;[m
[31m-    quick-tap-ms = <125>;[m
[31m-    global-quick-tap;[m
[31m-    bindings = <&kp>, <&kp>;[m
[31m-)[m
[31m-```[m
[31m-[m
[31m-This creates a custom "homerow mod" that can be added to the keymap using `&hrm`. For example,[m
[31m-`&hrm LSHIFT T` creates a key that yields `T` on tap and `LSHIFT` on hold.[m
[31m-[m
[31m-#### Example 2: Creating a custom tap-dance key[m
[31m-[m
[31m-```C++[m
[31m-ZMK_BEHAVIOR(ss_cw, tap_dance,[m
[31m-    tapping-term-ms = <200>;[m
[31m-    bindings = <&sk LSHFT>, <&caps_word>;[m
[31m-)[m
[31m-```[m
[31m-This behavior yields sticky-shift on tap and caps-word on double tap. It can be added to[m
[31m-the keymap using `&ss_cw`. [m
[31m-[m
[31m-#### Example 3: Creating a custom "win-sleep" macro[m
[31m-[m
[31m-```C++[m
[31m-ZMK_BEHAVIOR(win_sleep, macro,[m
[31m-    wait-ms = <100>;[m
[31m-    tap-ms = <5>;[m
[31m-    bindings = <&kp LG(X) &kp U &kp S>;[m
[31m-)[m
[31m-```[m
[31m-[m
[31m-This creates a "Windows sleep macro" that can be added to the keymap using `&win_sleep`.[m
[31m-[m
[31m-### ZMK\_LAYER[m
[31m-[m
[31m-`ZMK_LAYER` adds new keymap layers to the configuration.[m
[31m-[m
[31m-**Syntax:** `ZMK_LAYER(name, layout, sensors)`[m
[31m-* `name`: a unique identifier string chosen by the user (it will be displayed on keyboards with appropriately configured displays)[m
[31m-* `layout`: the layout specification using the same syntax as the `bindings`[m
[31m-  property of the [ZMK keymap configuration](https://zmk.dev/docs/config/keymap)[m
[31m-* `sensors` (optional): provides sensor-specification if specified[m
[31m-[m
[31m-Multiple layers can be added with repeated calls of `ZMK_LAYER`. They will be ordered[m
[31m-in the same order in which they are created, with the first-specified layer being[m
[31m-the "lowest" one ([see here for details](https://zmk.dev/docs/features/keymaps#layers)).[m
[31m-[m
[31m-#### Example usage[m
[31m-```C++[m
[31m-ZMK_LAYER(default_layer,[m
[31m-     // ╭─────────────┬─────────────┬─────────────┬─────────────┬─────────────╮   ╭─────────────┬─────────────┬─────────────┬─────────────┬─────────────╮[m
[31m-          &kp Q         &kp W         &kp F         &kp P         &kp B             &kp J         &kp L         &kp U         &kp Y         &kp SQT[m
[31m-     // ├─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┤   ├─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┤[m
[31m-          &hrm LGUI A   &hrm LALT R   &hrm LCTRL S  &hrm LSHFT T  &kp G             &kp M         &hrm RSHFT N  &hrm LCTRL E  &hrm LALT I   &hrm LGUI O[m
[31m-     // ├─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┤   ├─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┤[m
[31m-          &kp Z         &kp X         &kp C         &kp D         &kp V             &kp K         &kp H         &kp COMMA     &kp DOT       &kp SEMI[m
[31m-     // ╰─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┤   ├─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┤[m
[31m-                                      &kp ESC       &lt NAV SPACE &kp TAB           &kp RET       &ss_cw        &bs_del_num[m
[31m-     //                             ╰─────────────┴──── ────────┴─────────────╯   ╰─────────────┴─────────────┴─────────────╯[m
[31m-)[m
[31m-[m
[31m-```[m
[31m-[m
[31m-### ZMK\_COMBO[m
[31m-[m
[31m-`ZMK_COMBO` defines new combos.[m
[31m-[m
[31m-**Syntax:** `ZMK_COMBO(name, bindings, keypos, layers, timeout)`[m
[31m-* `name`: a unique identifier string chosen by the user (usually there is not reason to reference this elsewhere)[m
[31m-* `binding`: the binding triggered by the combo (this can be any stock or previously defined behavior)[m
[31m-* `keypos`: a list of 2 or more key positions that trigger the combo (e.g., `12[m
[31m-  13`). Note that the mapping from key positions to keys depends on your keyboard. To facilitate [m
[31m-  the combo setup and increase portability, one can use key-position helpers instead.[m
[31m-  See [below](#key-position-helpers) on how to use them.[m
[31m-* `layers`: a list of layers for which the combo is active (e.g., `0 1` for the first[m
[31m-  two layers). If set to `ALL` the combo is active on all layers.[m
[31m-* `timeout` (optional): combo timeout in ms. If omitted the timeout is set to the[m
[31m-  global value of `COMBO_TERM`, which defaults to 30ms and can be overwritten by the[m
[31m-  user as in the second example below.[m
[31m-[m
[31m-#### Example: escape combo[m
[31m-[m
[31m-```C++[m
[31m-ZMK_COMBO(esc,  &kp ESC, 0 1, ALL, 25)[m
[31m-```[m
[31m-This creates an "escape" combo that is active on all layers and which is triggered when[m
[31m-the 0th and 1st keys are[m
[31m-pressed jointly within 25ms.[m
[31m-[m
[31m-#### Example: copy and paste combos (using global COMBO_TERM)[m
[31m-[m
[31m-```C++[m
[31m-#undef COMBO_TERM[m
[31m-#define COMBO_TERM 50[m
[31m-ZMK_COMBO(copy,  &kp LC(C), 12 13, ALL)[m
[31m-ZMK_COMBO(paste, &kp LC(V), 13 14, ALL)[m
[31m-```[m
[31m-This sets the global combo timeout to 50ms, and then creates two combos which both are[m
[31m-active on all layers. The first combo is triggered when the 12th and 13th keys are[m
[31m-pressed jointly within the `COMBO_TERM`, sending <kbd>Ctrl</kbd> + <kbd>C</kbd>. The[m
[31m-second combo is triggered when the 13th and 14th keys are pressed jointly, sending[m
[31m-<kbd>Ctrl</kbd> + <kbd>V</kbd>.[m
[31m-[m
[31m-### ZMK\_CONDITIONAL\_LAYER[m
[31m-[m
[31m-This sets up tri-layer conditions.[m
[31m-[m
[31m-**Syntax:** `ZMK_CONDITIONAL_LAYER(if_layers, then_layers)`[m
[31m-* `if_layers`: a list of layers which trigger the `then_layer` if simultaneously active[m
[31m-* `then_layer`: the layer which is activated when the if-condition is met. Due to ZMK's[m
[31m-  layering model, it should generally have a higher number than the `if_layers`[m
[31m-[m
[31m-For instance, this triggers "layer 3" if layers "1" and "2" are[m
[31m-simultaneously active. [m
[31m-```C++[m
[31m-ZMK_CONDITIONAL_LAYER(1 2, 3)[m
[31m-```[m
[31m-Mind that ZMK's layer numbering starts at 0. One can use layer[m
[31m-definitions, as demonstrated in [example.keymap](example.keymap), to simplify life.[m
[31m-[m
[31m-### ZMK\_UNICODE[m
[31m-[m
[31m-There are two macros that create new unicode characters that[m
[31m-can be added to the keymap. `ZMK_UNICODE_SINGLE` creates single unicode characters such[m
[31m-as <kbd>€</kbd>, and `ZMK_UNICODE_PAIR` creates pairs of shifted/unshifted unicode[m
[31m-characters that are useful for specifying international characters such as[m
[31m-<kbd>ä</kbd>/<kbd>Ä</kbd> or <kbd>δ</kbd>/<kbd>Δ</kbd>.[m
[31m-[m
[31m-[m
[31m-**Syntax:** `ZMK_UNICODE_SINGLE(name, L0, L1, L2, L3)`[m
[31m-* `name:` a unique string chosen by the user (e.g., `my_char`). The unicode character  can[m
[31m-  be added to the keymap using `&name` (e.g., `&my_char`)[m
[31m-* `L0` to `L3`: a 4-digit sequence defining the unicode string using standard [ZMK key[m
[31m-  codes](https://zmk.dev/docs/codes/keyboard-keypad)[m
[31m-[m
[31m-**Syntax:** `ZMK_UNICODE_PAIR(name, L0, L1, L2, L3, U0, U1, U2, U3)`[m
[31m-* `name:` a unique string chosen by the user (e.g., `my_char`). The unicode character  can[m
[31m-  be added to the keymap using `&name` (e.g., `&my_char`)[m
[31m-* `L0` to `L3`: a 4-digit sequence defining the unshifted unicode string[m
[31m-* `U0` to `U3`: a 4-digit sequence defining the shifted unicode string (which is send when[m
[31m-  holding <kbd>Shift</kbd> while pressing <kbd>&name</kbd>)[m
[31m-[m
[31m-Note: 5-digit unicode characters are currently not supported (but would be easy to add[m
[31m-if there is interest).[m
[31m-[m
[31m-#### Example 1: Euro sign (€)[m
[31m-[m
[31m-```C++[m
[31m-ZMK_UNICODE_SINGLE(euro_sign, N2, N0, A, C)[m
[31m-```[m
[31m-This creates a Euro character that can be added to the keymap using `&euro_sign`.[m
[31m-[m
[31m-#### Example 2: German umlauts (ä/Ä, ö/Ö, ü/Ü)[m
[31m-[m
[31m-```C++[m
[31m-//                name     unshifted         shifted[m
[31m-ZMK_UNICODE_PAIR( de_ae,   N0, N0,  E, N4,   N0, N0,  C, N4 )[m
[31m-ZMK_UNICODE_PAIR( de_oe,   N0, N0,  F, N6,   N0, N0,  D, N6 )[m
[31m-ZMK_UNICODE_PAIR( de_ue,   N0, N0,  F,  C,   N0, N0,  D,  C )[m
[31m-```[m
[31m-The creates "umlaut" pairs that can be added to the keymap using `&de_ae`, `&de_oe` and `&de_ue`.[m
[31m-[m
[31m-#### Dependencies for unicode[m
[31m-[m
[31m-[m
[31m-* `ZMK_UNICODE_PAIR` requires a current ZMK after [PR[m
[31m-  #1412](https://github.com/zmkfirmware/zmk/pull/1412) was merged into main. If you are[m
[31m-  building with Github Actions using the default `west.yml` you are all set.[m
[31m-  <!-- If you need help maintaining[m
[31m-  your own ZMK repository, check out [this[m
[31m-  guide](https://gist.github.com/urob/68a1e206b2356a01b876ed02d3f542c7). If you don't[m
[31m-  want to maintain your own ZMK repository, you can use ZMK's [beta[m
[31m-  testing](https://zmk.dev/docs/features/beta-testing) feature to configure Github[m
[31m-  Actions to build against a patched remote branch of ZMK. To do so, replace the[m
[31m-  contents of `west.yml` in your `zmk-config/config` directory with the following[m
[31m-  contents, which adds the required patch:[m
[31m-    ```[m
[31m-    manifest:[m
[31m-      remotes:[m
[31m-        - name: urob[m
[31m-          url-base: https://github.com/urob[m
[31m-      projects:[m
[31m-        - name: zmk[m
[31m-          remote: urob[m
[31m-          revision: fix-mod-morph[m
[31m-          import: app/west.yml[m
[31m-      self:[m
[31m-        path: config[m
[31m-    ```[m
[31m-    -->[m
[31m-* The input of unicode characters differs across operating systems. By[m
[31m-    default, `ZMK_UNICODE` is configured for Windows (using WinCompose). To set it up[m
[31m-    for another OS, set the variable[m
[31m-    `HOST_OS` **before** sourcing `helper.h`.[m
[31m-[m
[31m-    For Linux use:[m
[31m-    ```C++[m
[31m-    #define HOST_OS 1  // set to 1 for Linux, default is 0 (Windows)[m
[31m-    #include helper.h[m
[31m-    ```[m
[31m-    For macOS/Windows-Alt-Codes use:[m
[31m-    ```C++[m
[31m-    #define HOST_OS 2  // set to 2 for macOS/Windows-Alt-Codes, default is 0 (Windows)[m
[31m-    #include helper.h[m
[31m-    ```[m
[31m-    This will send unicode characters using the OS's default input channels.[m
[31m-    For non-default input channels or for other operating systems, one can instead set the[m
[31m-    variables `OS_UNICODE_LEAD` and `OS_UNICODE_TRAIL` to the character sequences that[m
[31m-    initialize/terminate the unicode input.[^2][m
[31m-[m
[31m-* On Windows and macOS there are additional requirements for unicode input to work. On[m
[31m-  Windows, one must install [WinCompose](https://github.com/samhocevar/wincompose) for[m
[31m-  full support (or use Win-Alt-Codes for limited support in select software). On[m
[31m-  macOS one must enable unicode input in the system preferences, by selecting [m
[31m-  `Unicode Hex Input` as input source.[m
[31m-[m
[31m-### International characters[m
[31m-[m
[31m-There are pre-defined definitions for international characters for a few languages  ---[m
[31m-currently Danish, French, German, Greek and Swedish (contributions are welcome)[^3].[m
[31m-These can be loaded by sourcing the corresponding files; e.g.:[m
[31m-```C++[m
[31m-#include "../zmk-nodefree-config/international_chars/danish.dtsi"[m
[31m-#include "../zmk-nodefree-config/international_chars/french.dtsi"[m
[31m-#include "../zmk-nodefree-config/international_chars/german.dtsi"[m
[31m-#include "../zmk-nodefree-config/international_chars/greek.dtsi"[m
[31m-#include "../zmk-nodefree-config/international_chars/swedish.dtsi"[m
[31m-```[m
[31m-Once sourced, international characters can be added to the keymap using, e.g., `&de_ae`,[m
[31m-`&dk_ae`, `&fr_a_grave`, `&el_alpha` or `&sv_ao` (each language has its own prefix; see[m
[31m-the language files for a complete list of available characters).[m
[31m-[m
[31m-**Dependencies:** These definitions make use of unicode in the background,[m
[31m-see the unicode section above for [prerequisites](#dependencies-for-unicode).[m
[31m-[m
[31m-**Note:** Windows-Alt-Codes use different keycode sequences than the[m
[31m-usual unicode sequences, requiring different definitions. Currently, they are[m
[31m-pre-defined for German:[m
[31m-```C++[m
[31m-#include "../zmk-nodefree-config/international_chars/german_alt.dtsi"[m
[31m-```[m
