[32m+[m[32m# zmk-nodefree-config[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mZMK lets user customize their keyboard layout by providing a Devicetree file[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m(`.keymap`). The specific syntax requirements of the Devicetree file format can,[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mhowever, make this process a bit daunting for new users.[m[41m [m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mThis repository provides simple convenience macros that simplify the configuration for[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mmany common use cases. It results in a "node-free" user configuration with a more[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mstreamlined syntax. Check out [example.keymap](example.keymap) to see it in action.[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mSee [changelog](#changelog) for latest changes.[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m## Overview[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mThe following convenience macros are provided:[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m1. `ZMK_BEHAVIOR` creates behaviors such as hold-taps, tap-dances or[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m   ZMK macros [\[doc\]](#zmk_behavior)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m2. `ZMK_LAYER` adds layers to the keymap [\[doc\]](#zmk_layer)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m3. `ZMK_COMBO` defines combos [\[doc\]](#zmk_combo)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m4. `ZMK_CONDITIONAL_LAYER` sets up "tri-layer" conditions [\[doc\]](#zmk_conditional_layer)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m5. `ZMK_UNICODE_SINGLE` and `ZMK_UNICODE_PAIR` create unicode characters [\[doc\]](#zmk_unicode)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m6. `international_chars` provides character definitions for some non-English languages[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m   [\[doc\]](#international-characters)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m7. `keypos_def` provides human-readable key position shortcuts for some popular[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m   keyboards that simplify the configuration of combos and positional hold-taps[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m   [\[doc\]](#key-position-helpers)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m## Quickstart[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m1. Copy this repository into the root folder of your zmk-config (or add as submodule[^1]). The[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m   folder structure should look as follows:[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m   ```[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    zmk-config[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m     ├── config[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m     │    ├── your.keyboard.conf[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m     │    ├── your_keyboard.keymap[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m     │    └── ...[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m     ├── zmk-nodefree-config[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m     │    ├── helper.h[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m     │    ├── ...[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m   ```[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m2. Source `helper.h` near the top of your `.keymap` file:[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    ```C++[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    #include "../zmk-nodefree-config/helper.h"[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    ```[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m3. Customize your keyboard's `.keymap` file. See [example.keymap](example.keymap) or [my[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m   personal zmk-config](https://github.com/urob/zmk-config/blob/main/config/base.keymap)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m   for a complete configuration, and read the documentation below for details.[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m## Configuration details[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m### ZMK\_BEHAVIOR[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m`ZMK_BEHAVIOR` can be used to create any of the following ZMK behaviors: caps-word,[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mhold-tap, key-repeat, macro, mod-morph, sticky-key, tap-dance or tri-state.[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m**Syntax:** `ZMK_BEHAVIOR(name, type, specification)`[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m* `name`: a unique string chosen by the user (e.g., `my_behavior`). The new behavior can[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  be added to the keymap using `&name` (e.g., `&my_behavior`).[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m* `type`: the behavior to be created. It must be one of the following:[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  `caps_word`, `hold_tap`, `key_repeat`, `macro`, `macro_one_param`,[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  `macro_two_param`, `mod_morph`, `sticky_key`, `tap_dance` or `tri_state`.[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  Note that multiword behaviors are separated by underscores (`_`).[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m* `specification`: the custom behavior code. It should contain the[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  body of the corresponding [ZMK behavior configuration](https://zmk.dev/docs/config/behaviors)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  without the `label`, `#binding-cells` and `compatible` properties and without the[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  surrounding node-specification.[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m#### Example 1: Creating a custom "homerow mod" tap-hold behavior[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m```C++[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mZMK_BEHAVIOR(hrm, hold_tap,[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    flavor = "balanced";[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    tapping-term-ms = <280>;[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    quick-tap-ms = <125>;[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    global-quick-tap;[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    bindings = <&kp>, <&kp>;[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mThis creates a custom "homerow mod" that can be added to the keymap using `&hrm`. For example,[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m`&hrm LSHIFT T` creates a key that yields `T` on tap and `LSHIFT` on hold.[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m#### Example 2: Creating a custom tap-dance key[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m```C++[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mZMK_BEHAVIOR(ss_cw, tap_dance,[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    tapping-term-ms = <200>;[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    bindings = <&sk LSHFT>, <&caps_word>;[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mThis behavior yields sticky-shift on tap and caps-word on double tap. It can be added to[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mthe keymap using `&ss_cw`.[m[41m [m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m#### Example 3: Creating a custom "win-sleep" macro[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m```C++[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mZMK_BEHAVIOR(win_sleep, macro,[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    wait-ms = <100>;[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    tap-ms = <5>;[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    bindings = <&kp LG(X) &kp U &kp S>;[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mThis creates a "Windows sleep macro" that can be added to the keymap using `&win_sleep`.[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m### ZMK\_LAYER[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m`ZMK_LAYER` adds new keymap layers to the configuration.[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m**Syntax:** `ZMK_LAYER(name, layout, sensors)`[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m* `name`: a unique identifier string chosen by the user (it will be displayed on keyboards with appropriately configured displays)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m* `layout`: the layout specification using the same syntax as the `bindings`[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  property of the [ZMK keymap configuration](https://zmk.dev/docs/config/keymap)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m* `sensors` (optional): provides sensor-specification if specified[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mMultiple layers can be added with repeated calls of `ZMK_LAYER`. They will be ordered[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32min the same order in which they are created, with the first-specified layer being[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mthe "lowest" one ([see here for details](https://zmk.dev/docs/features/keymaps#layers)).[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m#### Example usage[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m```C++[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mZMK_LAYER(default_layer,[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m     // ╭─────────────┬─────────────┬─────────────┬─────────────┬─────────────╮   ╭─────────────┬─────────────┬─────────────┬─────────────┬─────────────╮[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m          &kp Q         &kp W         &kp F         &kp P         &kp B             &kp J         &kp L         &kp U         &kp Y         &kp SQT[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m     // ├─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┤   ├─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┤[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m          &hrm LGUI A   &hrm LALT R   &hrm LCTRL S  &hrm LSHFT T  &kp G             &kp M         &hrm RSHFT N  &hrm LCTRL E  &hrm LALT I   &hrm LGUI O[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m     // ├─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┤   ├─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┤[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m          &kp Z         &kp X         &kp C         &kp D         &kp V             &kp K         &kp H         &kp COMMA     &kp DOT       &kp SEMI[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m     // ╰─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┤   ├─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────┤[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m                                      &kp ESC       &lt NAV SPACE &kp TAB           &kp RET       &ss_cw        &bs_del_num[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m     //                             ╰─────────────┴──── ────────┴─────────────╯   ╰─────────────┴─────────────┴─────────────╯[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m### ZMK\_COMBO[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m`ZMK_COMBO` defines new combos.[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m**Syntax:** `ZMK_COMBO(name, bindings, keypos, layers, timeout)`[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m* `name`: a unique identifier string chosen by the user (usually there is not reason to reference this elsewhere)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m* `binding`: the binding triggered by the combo (this can be any stock or previously defined behavior)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m* `keypos`: a list of 2 or more key positions that trigger the combo (e.g., `12[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  13`). Note that the mapping from key positions to keys depends on your keyboard. To facilitate[m[41m [m
[32m+[m[32m  the combo setup and increase portability, one can use key-position helpers instead.[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  See [below](#key-position-helpers) on how to use them.[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m* `layers`: a list of layers for which the combo is active (e.g., `0 1` for the first[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  two layers). If set to `ALL` the combo is active on all layers.[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m* `timeout` (optional): combo timeout in ms. If omitted the timeout is set to the[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  global value of `COMBO_TERM`, which defaults to 30ms and can be overwritten by the[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  user as in the second example below.[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m#### Example: escape combo[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m```C++[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mZMK_COMBO(esc,  &kp ESC, 0 1, ALL, 25)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mThis creates an "escape" combo that is active on all layers and which is triggered when[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mthe 0th and 1st keys are[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mpressed jointly within 25ms.[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m#### Example: copy and paste combos (using global COMBO_TERM)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m```C++[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m#undef COMBO_TERM[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m#define COMBO_TERM 50[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mZMK_COMBO(copy,  &kp LC(C), 12 13, ALL)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mZMK_COMBO(paste, &kp LC(V), 13 14, ALL)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mThis sets the global combo timeout to 50ms, and then creates two combos which both are[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mactive on all layers. The first combo is triggered when the 12th and 13th keys are[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mpressed jointly within the `COMBO_TERM`, sending <kbd>Ctrl</kbd> + <kbd>C</kbd>. The[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32msecond combo is triggered when the 13th and 14th keys are pressed jointly, sending[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m<kbd>Ctrl</kbd> + <kbd>V</kbd>.[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m### ZMK\_CONDITIONAL\_LAYER[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mThis sets up tri-layer conditions.[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m**Syntax:** `ZMK_CONDITIONAL_LAYER(if_layers, then_layers)`[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m* `if_layers`: a list of layers which trigger the `then_layer` if simultaneously active[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m* `then_layer`: the layer which is activated when the if-condition is met. Due to ZMK's[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  layering model, it should generally have a higher number than the `if_layers`[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mFor instance, this triggers "layer 3" if layers "1" and "2" are[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32msimultaneously active.[m[41m [m
[32m+[m[32m```C++[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mZMK_CONDITIONAL_LAYER(1 2, 3)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mMind that ZMK's layer numbering starts at 0. One can use layer[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mdefinitions, as demonstrated in [example.keymap](example.keymap), to simplify life.[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m### ZMK\_UNICODE[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mThere are two macros that create new unicode characters that[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mcan be added to the keymap. `ZMK_UNICODE_SINGLE` creates single unicode characters such[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mas <kbd>€</kbd>, and `ZMK_UNICODE_PAIR` creates pairs of shifted/unshifted unicode[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mcharacters that are useful for specifying international characters such as[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m<kbd>ä</kbd>/<kbd>Ä</kbd> or <kbd>δ</kbd>/<kbd>Δ</kbd>.[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m**Syntax:** `ZMK_UNICODE_SINGLE(name, L0, L1, L2, L3)`[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m* `name:` a unique string chosen by the user (e.g., `my_char`). The unicode character  can[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  be added to the keymap using `&name` (e.g., `&my_char`)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m* `L0` to `L3`: a 4-digit sequence defining the unicode string using standard [ZMK key[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  codes](https://zmk.dev/docs/codes/keyboard-keypad)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m**Syntax:** `ZMK_UNICODE_PAIR(name, L0, L1, L2, L3, U0, U1, U2, U3)`[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m* `name:` a unique string chosen by the user (e.g., `my_char`). The unicode character  can[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  be added to the keymap using `&name` (e.g., `&my_char`)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m* `L0` to `L3`: a 4-digit sequence defining the unshifted unicode string[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m* `U0` to `U3`: a 4-digit sequence defining the shifted unicode string (which is send when[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  holding <kbd>Shift</kbd> while pressing <kbd>&name</kbd>)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mNote: 5-digit unicode characters are currently not supported (but would be easy to add[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mif there is interest).[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m#### Example 1: Euro sign (€)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m```C++[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mZMK_UNICODE_SINGLE(euro_sign, N2, N0, A, C)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mThis creates a Euro character that can be added to the keymap using `&euro_sign`.[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m#### Example 2: German umlauts (ä/Ä, ö/Ö, ü/Ü)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m```C++[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m//                name     unshifted         shifted[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mZMK_UNICODE_PAIR( de_ae,   N0, N0,  E, N4,   N0, N0,  C, N4 )[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mZMK_UNICODE_PAIR( de_oe,   N0, N0,  F, N6,   N0, N0,  D, N6 )[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mZMK_UNICODE_PAIR( de_ue,   N0, N0,  F,  C,   N0, N0,  D,  C )[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mThe creates "umlaut" pairs that can be added to the keymap using `&de_ae`, `&de_oe` and `&de_ue`.[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m#### Dependencies for unicode[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m* `ZMK_UNICODE_PAIR` requires a current ZMK after [PR[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  #1412](https://github.com/zmkfirmware/zmk/pull/1412) was merged into main. If you are[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  building with Github Actions using the default `west.yml` you are all set.[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  <!-- If you need help maintaining[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  your own ZMK repository, check out [this[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  guide](https://gist.github.com/urob/68a1e206b2356a01b876ed02d3f542c7). If you don't[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  want to maintain your own ZMK repository, you can use ZMK's [beta[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  testing](https://zmk.dev/docs/features/beta-testing) feature to configure Github[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  Actions to build against a patched remote branch of ZMK. To do so, replace the[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  contents of `west.yml` in your `zmk-config/config` directory with the following[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  contents, which adds the required patch:[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    ```[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    manifest:[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m      remotes:[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m        - name: urob[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m          url-base: https://github.com/urob[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m      projects:[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m        - name: zmk[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m          remote: urob[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m          revision: fix-mod-morph[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m          import: app/west.yml[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m      self:[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m        path: config[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    ```[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    -->[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m* The input of unicode characters differs across operating systems. By[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    default, `ZMK_UNICODE` is configured for Windows (using WinCompose). To set it up[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    for another OS, set the variable[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    `HOST_OS` **before** sourcing `helper.h`.[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    For Linux use:[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    ```C++[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    #define HOST_OS 1  // set to 1 for Linux, default is 0 (Windows)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    #include helper.h[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    ```[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    For macOS/Windows-Alt-Codes use:[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    ```C++[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    #define HOST_OS 2  // set to 2 for macOS/Windows-Alt-Codes, default is 0 (Windows)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    #include helper.h[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    ```[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    This will send unicode characters using the OS's default input channels.[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    For non-default input channels or for other operating systems, one can instead set the[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    variables `OS_UNICODE_LEAD` and `OS_UNICODE_TRAIL` to the character sequences that[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    initialize/terminate the unicode input.[^2][m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m* On Windows and macOS there are additional requirements for unicode input to work. On[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  Windows, one must install [WinCompose](https://github.com/samhocevar/wincompose) for[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  full support (or use Win-Alt-Codes for limited support in select software). On[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  macOS one must enable unicode input in the system preferences, by selecting[m[41m [m
[32m+[m[32m  `Unicode Hex Input` as input source.[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m### International characters[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mThere are pre-defined definitions for international characters for a few languages  ---[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mcurrently Danish, French, German, Greek and Swedish (contributions are welcome)[^3].[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mThese can be loaded by sourcing the corresponding files; e.g.:[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m```C++[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m#include "../zmk-nodefree-config/international_chars/danish.dtsi"[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m#include "../zmk-nodefree-config/international_chars/french.dtsi"[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m#include "../zmk-nodefree-config/international_chars/german.dtsi"[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m#include "../zmk-nodefree-config/international_chars/greek.dtsi"[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m#include "../zmk-nodefree-config/international_chars/swedish.dtsi"[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mOnce sourced, international characters can be added to the keymap using, e.g., `&de_ae`,[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m`&dk_ae`, `&fr_a_grave`, `&el_alpha` or `&sv_ao` (each language has its own prefix; see[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mthe language files for a complete list of available characters).[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m**Dependencies:** These definitions make use of unicode in the background,[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32msee the unicode section above for [prerequisites](#dependencies-for-unicode).[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m**Note:** Windows-Alt-Codes use different keycode sequences than the[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32musual unicode sequences, requiring different definitions. Currently, they are[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mpre-defined for German:[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m```C++[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m#include "../zmk-nodefree-config/international_chars/german_alt.dtsi"[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m### Key-position helpers[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mCertain configuration options such as combos and positional hold-taps are based on the[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mphysical position of keys on the keyboard. This can be cumbersome and reduces[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mportability of configuration files across keyboards with different layouts.[m[41m [m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mTo increase portability and ease of use, this repo provides optional key-position[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mhelpers for some popular keyboard layouts (58-key boards such as Lily58, 48-key boards[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32msuch as Planck, 42-key boards such as Corne, 36-key boards and 34-key boards).[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mThese key-position helpers provide a map from the physical key positions to human-readable shortcuts.[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mAll shortcuts are of the following form:[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m* `L/R` for **L**eft/**R**ight hand[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m* `T/M/B/H` for **T**op/**M**iddle/**B**ottom and t**H**umb row.[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m* `0/1/2/3/4` for the finger position starting from the inside (`0` is the inner[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  index-finger column, `1` is the home position of the index finger, ..., `4` is the home[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m  position of the pinkie)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mFor instance, the shortcuts layout for a 36-key board looks as follows:[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m╭─────────────────────┬─────────────────────╮[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m│ LT4 LT3 LT2 LT1 LT0 │ RT0 RT1 RT2 RT3 RT4 │[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m│ LM4 LM3 LM2 LM1 LM0 │ RM0 RM1 RM2 RM3 RM4 │[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m│ LB4 LB3 LB2 LB1 LB0 │ RB0 RB1 RB2 RB3 RB4 │[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m╰───────╮ LH2 LH1 LH0 │ RH0 RH1 RH2 ╭───────╯[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m        ╰─────────────┴─────────────╯[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mSchematics for all supported keyboards can be found in the corresponding[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mdefinition files in the `keypos_def` folder.[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mTo use these key-position helpers, source the definition file for your keyboard[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32minto your `.keymap` file. E.g., for a 36-key board, use:[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m```C++[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m#include "../zmk-nodefree-config/keypos_def/keypos_36keys.h"[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m#### Example 1: Defining combos using key-position helpers[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m```C++[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mZMK_COMBO(copy,  &kp LC(C), LB2 LB3, ALL)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mZMK_COMBO(paste, &kp LC(V), LB1 LB2, ALL)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mThis defines a "copy"-combo for the middle + ring finger on the left bottom row, and a[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m"paste"-combo for the index + middle finger on the left bottom row. Both combos are active on all layers.[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m#### Example 2: Home-row mods with positional hold-taps[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mHere we use ZMK's [positional[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mhold-tap](https://zmk.dev/docs/behaviors/hold-tap#positional-hold-tap-and-hold-trigger-key-positions)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mfeature to make home-row mods only trigger with "opposite hand" keys. Using[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mkey-position helpers makes this straightforward:[m[41m [m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m```C++[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m#define KEYS_L LT0 LT1 LT2 LT3 LT4 LM0 LM1 LM2 LM3 LM4 LB0 LB1 LB2 LB3 LB4  // left-hand keys[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m#define KEYS_R RT0 RT1 RT2 RT3 RT4 RM0 RM1 RM2 RM3 RM4 RB0 RB1 RB2 RB3 RB4  // right-hand keys[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m#define THUMBS LH2 LH1 LH0 RH0 RH1 RH2                                      // thumb keys[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mZMK_BEHAVIOR(hml, hold_tap,  // left-hand HRMs[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    flavor = "balanced";[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    tapping-term-ms = <280>;[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    quick-tap-ms = <125>;[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    global-quick-tap;[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    bindings = <&kp>, <&kp>;[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    hold-trigger-key-positions = <KEYS_R THUMBS>;[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32mZMK_BEHAVIOR(hmr, hold_tap,  // right-hand HRMs[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    flavor = "balanced";[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    tapping-term-ms = <280>;[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    quick-tap-ms = <125>;[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    global-quick-tap;[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    bindings = <&kp>, <&kp>;[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m    hold-trigger-key-positions = <KEYS_L THUMBS>;[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m)[m[41m[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m[41m[m
